          "title": "The high priest's death — the chapter's theological apex",
          "body": "Verse 25 introduces the most theologically dense element of the chapter: the manslayer confined to the refuge city must remain there until the death of the high priest anointed with the holy oil. The text gives no explanation. No mechanism is stated, no rationale offered, no cross-reference supplied within the chapter itself. The law simply is: the high priest's death releases the manslayer to return to the land of his possession (35:28). Verse 32 closes the door on any shortcut — you cannot ransom the manslayer out of confinement before the priest dies. What does the high priest's death accomplish? The most natural reading, held across Jewish interpretive tradition and explicit in the New Testament (Hebrews 9:11–15), is that the high priest bore a representative relationship to the people: his life covered them, his death released what his life had been holding. Calvin observed that just as the high priest's life bound the manslayer, so his death loosed him — and that this death-as-release is the pattern the NT applies to Christ, whose death releases all who have fled to Him from the condemnation they deserved. This is not allegorizing; it is the canonical logic of typology — real institutions pointing beyond themselves to their ultimate referent."
